ξ 117. Sponsors and fidepromis· sors are osten employed for addi· tional security; an adstipulator is only employed to secure payment after our death. Our own stipula- tion for this is void, and therefore we associate with ourselves an ad- stipulator, who sues after our death, and is compelled by an action of mandate to hand over to our suc· cessor whatever he recovers.

ξ 118. The rules which govem the sponsor and fidepromissor are similar, and very unlike thom which govern the fidejussor.

§lla The former are adjuncta of none but verbal contracte, though (like fidejussions) they are some- times effective when the principa] promisor is not validly bound, as, for instance, when a woman or ward contracts without the guardian’s authority, or a person promises a payment after his death. It is a moot question when a slave or. alien promises by the term spondeo, whe- ther his sponsor or fidepromissor is effectively bound. A fidejussor may accompany any obligations, whether real, verbal, literal, or eon· sensual‚ and whether civil or natural. Accordingly, he may be bound for the obligation of a slave either to a stranger or to his master.
